form.longName: PhenX Dental Caries Experience Prevalence - PX080301
form.preferredDefinition: The Decayed, Missing, or Filled Tooth Surfaces (DMFS) Index is used by a dentist or dental hygienist to determine the prevalence of coronal caries in permanent and primary teeth through an examination that records the three components.

question.questionText: The Decayed, Missing, or Filled Tooth Surfaces Index is used by a dentist or dental hygienist to determine the prevalence of coronal caries in permanent and primary teeth through an examination that records the three components. This variable records tooth code to assess the Missing Teeth (the M Component of the DMFS Index) for tooth Upper Right 2M

validValue.meaningText: Sound permanent tooth (no decay or filling on any surface)
Missing due to dental disease (caries/periodontal disease)
Missing due to other causes (orthodontic/traumatic or other non-disease)
Missing due to dental disease but replaced by a fixed restoration
Missing due to other causes but replaced by a fixed restoration
Missing due to dental disease but replaced by a removable restoration
Missing due to other causes but replaced by a removable restoration
Permanent root tip is present but no restorative replacement is present
Permanent root tip is present but a restorative replacement is present
Tooth present, condition cannot be assessed

question.questionText: The Decayed, Missing, or Filled Tooth Surfaces Index is used by a dentist or dental hygienist to determine the prevalence of coronal caries in permanent and primary teeth through an examination that records the three components. This variable records tooth surface code to assess the Decayed Tooth Surfaces (the D component of the DMFS Index) and Filled Tooth Surfaces (the F component of the DMFS Index) for tooth Upper Right 2M

validValue.meaningText: Crown (short call for both primary and permanent teeth)
